title: Segfault compiling with -C link-arg=-fuse-ld=lld -C link-arg=-s

labels.name: A-linkage
labels.description: Area: linking into static, shared libraries and binaries

labels.name: I-crash
labels.description: Issue: The compiler crashes (SIGSEGV, SIGABRT, etc). Use I-ICE instead when the compiler panics.

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

body:
It's very possible I'm doing something stupid/wrong, but compiling some rust projects with env `RUSTFLAGS="-C link-arg=-fuse-ld=lld -C link-arg=-s"` appears to cause segfaults. Maybe that's not a valid combination of switches to put together but it does work on some projects. I was just experimenting with different flags so this isn't a critical issue for me just thought I'd report it. I can always get this to crash on the alacritty project (see steps below, along with the output of running the command). It crashes on stable as well as nightly. If this is just a bad combination, feel free to close the issue. Thanks! ### Code ```Rust git co git@github.com:alacritty/alacritty.git cd alacritty RUSTFLAGS="-C link-arg=-fuse-ld=lld -C link-arg=-s" RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo build -vv ``` ### Meta `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` rustc 1.46.0 (04488afe3 2020-08-24) binary: rustc commit-hash: 04488afe34512aa4c33566eb16d8c912a3ae04f9 commit-date: 2020-08-24 host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu release: 1.46.0 LLVM version: 10.0 ``` ### Error output ``` ```
